			<title>Humble Origin Bundle</title>
			<link>http://www.graffe.com/forums/showthread.php?75662-Humble-Origin-Bundle&amp;goto=newpost</link>
			<pubDate>Tue, 20 Aug 2013 10:53:56 GMT</pubDate>
			<description>EA and Humble Bundle have a bundle of EA games. https://www.humblebundle.com/ All of the proceeds not given to Humble Bundle are split up among five charities: Human Rights Campaign, watsi, American Cancer Society, American Red Cross, San Francisco AIDS Foundation. I believe this has been the...</description>
			<content:encoded><![CDATA[<div>EA and Humble Bundle have a bundle of EA games. <a href="https://www.humblebundle.com/" target="_blank" rel="nofollow">https://www.humblebundle.com/</a> All of the proceeds not given to Humble Bundle are split up among five charities: Human Rights Campaign, watsi, American Cancer Society, American Red Cross, San Francisco AIDS Foundation. I believe this has been the fastest selling Humble Bundle yet. Seen a fair amount of people gloating about giving a dollar to charity for games they will pretend to not like. The way people seek approval from others over the internet by being intensely negative is really starting to bug me.<br />
<br />
Anyway, here are the games currently available as part of the bundle: You get keys for Origin, and keys for Steam (for the older titles).<br />
<br />
Dead Space 1 <br />
Dead Space 3 (yeah, they skipped 2) <br />
Crysis 2<br />
Mirror's Edge<br />
Medal of Honor<br />
Burnout Paradise: Ultimate<br />
<br />
If you spend more than the average (currently $4.80 or so), you also get:<br />
<br />
Battlefield 3<br />
Sims 3<br />
<br />
There are rumors more games will be added at the halfway point, Dead Space 2 seems a given. Bulletstorm has been suggested. I secretly hope for Crysis 3 but don't expect it.<br />
<br />
I've already got most of these games, but went ahead and donated for Mirror's Edge. It's a decent bundle, good games but not their best games. But since it's illegal to mention EA on the internet without griping about them, I will point out that both Battlefield 3 and the Sims 3 have a freak load of DLC that they no doubt hope people will feel compelled to buy once trying the games. This is also obviously a fairly easy way to get more people on Origin.<br />
<br />
If you are curious and/or tempted, here are my opinions on each of the games in the bundle: Games in parentheses are not confirmed.<br />
<br />
<div style="margin:20px; margin-top:5px">
<div class="smallfont" style="margin-bottom:2px"><b>Spoiler</b> for <i>impressions</i>: <input type="button" value="Show" style="width:45px;font-size:10px;margin:0px;padding:0px;" onClick="if (this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display != 'inline') { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'inline'; this.value = 'Hide'; } else { this.parentNode.parentNode.getElementsByTagName('div')[1].getElementsByTagName('div')[0].style.display = 'none';  this.value = 'Show'; }">
</div>
<div class="alt2" style="margin: 0px; padding: 6px; border: 1px inset;">
<div style="display: none;">
<br />
Dead Space 1 - Space survival horror, very tense atmosphere. Feels a bit unpolished at times, and can be annoying, but the things it does well are never topped by the sequels.<br />
(Dead Space 2) - A bit more of an action game than the first one, but the formula isn't ruined nearly as much as it was in the Resident Evil games. My least favorite in the series.<br />
Dead Space 3 - Takes what they started with 2 and perfects it. 1 does atmosphere better, 3 does everything else better. Neither the DLC nor the co-op ruin the game.<br />
<br />
Crysis 2 - Plays more like a FEAR game than Crysis 1. If you can get over this, the gunplay and suit powers are better, but the game in general is mediocre. Fun combat, bleh everything else.<br />
Battlefield 3 - I liked the previous games more, but it still has a few things going for it.<br />
(Bulletstorm) - Probably my favorite game on this list. It's a dumb action shooter with cool combo mechanics. Shoot guys, kick guys, use a lasso to fling guys around. It's great.<br />
<br />
Medal of Honor - Haven't played. Heard it's just a mediocre CoD clone. Campaign is 4 hours long, which is actually perfect for me when allowed to choose my own price. An appetizer is all I want.<br />
Mirror's Edge - Haven't played. Unique idea hampered by a few annoying design decisions.<br />
Burnout - Haven't played. Supposed to be a pretty good open world racer.<br />
Sims 3 - Haven't played. Doesn't need an explanation anyway. Do you want to watch cartoon people use the toilet? Then this game is for you!<br />
<br />
 
</div>
</div>
</div><br />
<br />
<br />
In somewhat related news, EA has a new policy where if you buy a game on the Origin store, you have within seven days of purchase, or within 24 hours of activating and playing a game, to return it for a refund. The stated purpose is to let people return games that don't run on their system. Too bad that policy wasn't in place for SimCity huh? :p I have already seen some poor fools talking about beating a game in 24 hours and then returning it for a refund. I predict more bitching and moaning to come when EA notices this and refuses the refund. Thinking about anything other than how to cheat a system is apparently hard.</div>

]]></content:encoded>
